{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9217d11e-d7cb-40c8-b0d2-785da6745b3a","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Log(\"Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Log(\"Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Log(\"Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Log(\"Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Log(\"Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Log(\"Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Log(\"Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n\nvoid Log(string state) =>\n    System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine($\"[Window] {state} at {DateTime.Now:T}\");\n```\n\n**Lifecycle order (typical):**\n\n| Transition | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | Created → Activated |\n| User switches away | Deactivated → Stopped |\n| User returns | Resumed → Activated |\n| App closed | Stopped → Destroying |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst only — use it to save state before the OS may terminate your app.\n\nYou can also override the corresponding virtual methods on a custom `Window` subclass (`OnCreated`, `OnActivated`, etc.) if you prefer inheritance over events.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c628d70c-1e94-4eac-9257-780aec4abdc6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development - I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":443,"requestId":"5036:BD0FA:1C1A0C0:1F1EB1A:69FA904F"},"id":"861e6bb9-2e52-4626-b8e0-c6f370349dac","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:50:33.366Z","parentId":"18d704d9-411f-4e75-961a-7eb34d3cf325"}
